 ensemble mean of three reanalyses and multi-model mean under HIST, and vertical blue dashed lines mark the 97.5% cumulative probabilities of an assumed normal distribution for the trends. c, d are the same as a, b, but for the global average intensity anomalies of surface droughts (c) and deep droughts (d).Extended Data Fig. 4 Projected changes in intensity of surface droughts and deep droughts over the globe.a Maps show the projected relative changes in intensity of surface droughts in three layers under SSP245 during 2061–2100 compared to those under HIST during 1981–2020. Stippling indicates that more than 60% of the models agree on the changes in intensity of surface droughts across the 13-model CMIP6 ensemble. c The red lines show global average intensity of surface droughts under SSP245 and SSP585 during 2015–2100. The time series show a significant positive trend (one-sided Mann-Kendall test, p < 0.01), and shading represents the standard deviation across the multi-model ensemble. b, d are the same as a, c, but for deep droughts. Basemaps in a and b from Natural Earth (https://www.naturalearthdata.com).Extended Data Fig. 5 Difference in duration and intensity between deep droughts and surface droughts over the globe.Map based on the MCD12C1 land cover information is aggregated to a 1° target resolution by considering the largest land cover class fraction per grid cell. The time series show differences in duration (left column) and intensity (right column) between deep droughts and surface droughts in forests, the Amazon rainforest, shrubs, savannahs under ALL during 1981–2014, as well as SSP245 and SSP585 during 2015–2100. Straight lines represent linear trends. These time series show a significant positive trend (one-sided Mann-Kendall test, p < 0.01), and shading represents the standard deviation across the multi-model ensemble. Basemap in a from Natural Earth (https://www.naturalearthdata.com).Extended Data Fig. 6 Contributions of different drivers to intensity of surface droughts and deep droughts.a, b Maps of normalized contributions of preceding hot extremes (TEM; Methods) to the intensity of surface droughts (a) and deep droughts (b) based on ensemble mean of three reanalyses. Only grid cells where the co-occurrence between droughts and preceding drivers is significantly higher than expected by chance (see Methods) are filled (Non-significance as white areas). c Bar charts show the regional mean contributions of preceding hot extremes, preceding precipitation deficits (PRE), and preceding vegetation greening (LAI) in three regions (western North America, Europe, and the Middle East; red dashed rectangles in a, b) (n = 3). Each reanalysis-based result is represented by a white diamond. The error bars represent the ±1 standard deviation range across three reanalyses. d, e (g, h) are the same as a, b, but for preceding precipitation deficits (preceding vegetation greening). f, i are the same as c, but for the tropics and eastern Asia (blue dashed rectangles in d, e) or the northern high latitudes (brown dashed rectangles in g, h). Stippling on the maps indicates that more than 40% contribution from the preceding hot extremes (a, b), more than 40% contribution from both the preceding precipitation deficits and hot extremes (d, e), and more than 40% contribution from the preceding vegetation greening (g, h). Basemaps in a,b,d,e,g and h from Natural Earth (https://www.naturalearthdata.com).Extended Data Fig. 7 Comparisons of soil moisture deficits based on reanalysis, satellite, and drought monitor system.Maps show the average spatial distribution of soil moisture deficits (soil moisture minus threshold) for 19–25 September 2007 based on ERA5-land and ESA-CCI, as well as USDM drought severity map during the same period. Basemaps from Natural Earth (https://www.naturalearthdata.com).Extended Data Fig. 8 Spatial distributions of station-based droughts with vertical structure.The spatial distributions of soil moisture stations from ISMN and OzNet. Color denotes the frequency of bottom-heavy droughts at the station scales. Error bars in the bottom-left subplot show the median of drought characteristics (duration: days; intensity: 10−3 m3∙m−3) and their 25% ~ 75% uncertainty, respectively. There are 338 stations in North America (n = 2,123 for top-heavy drought and n = 2,055 for bottom-heavy drought), 35 in Australia (n = 139 for top-heavy drought and n = 176 for bottom-heavy drought), 8 in Europe (n = 34 for top-heavy drought and n = 25 for bottom-heavy drought), and 6 in Africa (n = 44 for top-heavy drought and n = 32 for bottom-heavy drought). Black dots present stations with the same geographic coordinates. Basemaps from Natural Earth (https://www.naturalearthdata.com).Supplementary informationSupplementary InformationSupplementary Notes 1–4, Figs. 1–12 and Tables 1 and 2.Reporting SummaryRights and permissionsSpringer Nature or its licensor (e.g. a society or other partner) holds exclusive rights to this article under a publishing agreement with the author(s) or other rightsholder(s); author self-archiving of the accepted manuscript version of this article is solely governed by the terms of such publishing agreement and applicable law.Reprints and permissionsAbout this articleCite this articleGuan, Y., Gu, X., Dai, A. et al. Anthropogenic enhancement of subsurface soil moisture droughts.
